 /><br />	if (current_cwd == dir_to_remove)<br />		return -EINVAL;<br /><br />while Digital UNIX and Linux just do not do that stupid check (and it <br />_is_ stupid, because it doesn't "protect" against anything). <br /><br />In fact, you don't even need two windows: do the following on Solaris (or <br />HP-UX):<br /><br />	kruuna$ cd /tmp<br />	/tmp<br />	kruuna$ mkdir X<br />	kruuna$ cd X<br />	/tmp/X<br />	kruuna$ ( cd ; rmdir /tmp/X )<br />	/home/fs/torvalds<br />	kruuna$ /bin/pwd<br />	pwd: cannot determine current directory!<br /><br />See? It's not the OS being "clever" and noticing that the directory is in<br />use, it's the OS being "anal" and permitting the rmdir() only if it's not the<br />cwd of the process trying to run. I don't see the point in that kind of<br />testing. <br /><br />		Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
